Azure Policy CANNOT require that a Private Endpoint already exists at creation time. Azure Policy CAN enforce “private only posture” by denying public network access
This is by design because:

 1. Private Endpoints are separate resources
 2. Often created after the PaaS resource
 3. Require VNet/DNS approvals

Correct enforcement model (Microsoft‑aligned):

Deny public network access → forces all traffic to be private → Private Endpoints can still be created later via the Portal

This fully satisfies: Traffic never traverses the public internet

Service		Enforced Control
Storage		Deny publicNetworkAccess = Enabled
Key Vault	Deny public network access
SQL Server	Deny public network access
Web App		Deny public access
Cosmos DB	Deny public network access

After this, Private Endpoints CAN still be created via the Portal.

Step‑by‑Step Implementation (Portal)

1. Azure Portal → Policy
2. Definitions → Create
3. Paste each custom policy JSON
4. Save policies

Now we need to create the Policy Initiative

1. Azure Portal → Policy
2. Go to Definitions
3. Click + Initiative definition
4. Fill in --> Name: Enforce-Private-Only-PaaS, Category: Security / Networking and Definition location: Management Group (recommended)
5. In Policies section: Click Add policy definition, Search and select each of the 5 custom policies and Add all of them to the initiative

Now Assign (Enable) the Initiative

Open the initiative
Click Assign
Choose scope: Management Group or Subscription
Enforcement mode: Enabled
Review + Create: Now the enforcement is active
